8/* SYNOPSIS

12/* int code;
13/*
14/* int dns_type(strval)
15/* const char *strval;
16/* DESCRIPTION
17/* dns_strtype() maps a name service lookup type to printable string.
18/* The result is for read-only purposes, and unknown codes share a
19/* common string buffer.
20/*
21/* dns_type() converts a name service lookup string value to a numeric
22/* code. A null result means the code was not found. The input can be

52 /*
53 * Mapping from type code to printable string. Some names are possibly not
54 * defined on every platform, so I have #ifdef-ed them all just to be safe.
55 */
56struct dns_type_map {
57 unsigned type;
58 const char *text;
59};

187/* dns_strtype - translate DNS query type to string */
188
189const char *dns_strtype(unsigned type)
190{
191 static VSTRING *unknown = 0;
192 unsigned i;
193
194 for (i = 0; i < sizeof(dns_type_map) / sizeof(dns_type_map[0]); i++)
195 if (dns_type_map[i].type == type)
196 return (dns_type_map[i].text);
197 if (unknown == 0)
198 unknown = vstring_alloc(sizeof("Unknown type XXXXXX"));
199 vstring_sprintf(unknown, "Unknown type %u", type);
200 return (vstring_str(unknown));
201}
202
203/* dns_type - translate string to DNS query type */
204
205unsigned dns_type(const char *text)
206{
207 unsigned i;
208
209 for (i = 0; i < sizeof(dns_type_map) / sizeof(dns_type_map[0]); i++)
210 if (strcasecmp(dns_type_map[i].text, text) == 0)
211 return (dns_type_map[i].type);
212 return (0);
213}
